post_text:
Three Important Updates:

1/2 day tomorrow (end at 11:30), Moving to the "yellow" phase of reopening next week, and Internet Cafes set to start on 9/28.

1/2 day - Please stay in remote learning tomorrow if you feel the health of your student might be affected by the air and/or if a half day is a hardship for your family. Our buses will be transporting with the windows up tomorrow. Please transport your student if you can. Our goal is for students to have an opportunity to engaged with teachers, limit the amount of mask breaks/exposure to outside air, take home meals, and we'll be keeping a close eye on how our high school building handles this environment.

Yellow Phase - starting next week, all K-5 students will move to 4-days-per-week onsite (M-TH)

Internet Cafes (launching 9/28) - A full 4 day schedule of after school access to Internet/tutoring from 4-6pm (open to all RESD students). More information to come.

post_text:
Tomorrow - 9/16 - we will be in remote learning due to air quality. While the air quality did improve some today, we are needing to make this call to give everyone the maximum amount of time to plan. If we did not have to take measures to mitigate COVID-19, it is possible that our decision might have been different. On top of COVID, our high school building infrastructure is old and outdated, while our new K-8 learning space is really equipped to handle this situation pretty well.

Our team is working extremely hard to navigate this situation and we are monitoring these sites closely as well as being in close communication with Lincoln County DOH:

https://www.iqair.com/us/air-quality-map

https://enviwa.ecology.wa.gov/home/map

https://www.airnow.gov/?city=Reardan&state=WA&country=USA

Please call with any questions or concerns or email at: esobotta@reardansd.net

Honored to serve,
Eric

Due to air qualityüî•üî•üî• - we are moving to REMOTE LEARNING tomorrow (no onsite learning). We are doing everything we can to still provide meals to the (65) students that requested them for tomorrow and will update you if we are not able to do so.
Elementary Students (M/W) - Please at a minimum read for 30 min., create an illustration about the smokey conditions and write about your illustration. T/TH cohort should already have your Monday assignments.
Secondary Students - Please check Google Classroom tomorrow for assignments.
If you need Internet access to download your assignments, we have extended the network into the drop off loop at the elementary so that you can download needed materials.
Please let us know if you have any questions at all.

Highline Grain Growers, Inc., in conjunction with the Washington Farm Bureau and the WSDA, donated 130 gallons of hand sanitizer, several sanitizer dispensers, and 500 face masks to the school district.

post_text:
ATTN: Senior Class of 2020, Parents, and Community Members... Please Join Us!

Friday Night Lights

Please Join us tomorrow night April 10th for the #bethelight campaign 20:20
We will be participating, along with schools across the country, to celebrate the Senior Class of 2020 and the Spring Sports that have come to a halt due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Our Football Stadium lights will be on for 20 minutes (8:20-8:40) at that time we invite our Senior Class of 2020 to drive around the track and be celebrated!
Parents and Community Members: Please enter track between 7:45 and 8:15 (at west entrance ambulance gate). You will be directed from there for parking instructions.
Seniors: Please be lined up on Aspen Street facing South by 8:15
*EVERYONE MUST REMAIN IN THEIR VEHICLE*
This is NOT an opportunity to bring people together physically.

Hope to see you there...
Stay Strong, Stay Healthy, Stay Apart!

post_text:
All RESD district staff were given a chance to stay home today and tomorrow to get their families settled, daycare arranged and prepare for a different kind of work for the next several weeks.

Staff will meet Wednesday and prepare student assignments to be sent home. Older students may be sent by email (unless they have no reception) and our youngest students will receive packets of worksheets for a week at a time. This is our best plans for now but we will work as a group to help refine the processes on Wednesday.

This is a difficult time but as a school and community, we can be resilient. My hope is that we grant each other compassion and grace during this time. Look for ways to help your neighbors and friends. Thank you in advance.

Marcus Morgan, Superintendent

Attention Students, Parents, and Community Members,

After jointly consulting with the Lincoln County Health Department, Lincoln County Road Department and legal counsel, the administration from Davenport, Harrington and Reardan-Edwall schools has made the decision that the school districts are no longer sponsoring the 2020 Prom. This decision was not made lightly, but with the advanced risk of COVID-19 in our communities and the poor road conditions, this is the safest option. We must hold the safety and well-being of our students as our top priority. We appreciate your support as we navigate this difficult time.

Sincerely,
The Administration of Davenport, Harrington, and Reardan-Edwall School Districts

Washington State FCCLA
April 12, 2019 at 7:20 AM ¬∑

Congratulations Reardan High School!! You are the 1st place FACTS Award Winner for Washington State and will receive $500!!

Reardan chose to address the problem of driving while under the influence with their project, ‚ÄúDrive Sober, Drive Safe‚Äù.

They partnered with their local fire and rescue, the county sheriff, Lincoln County Drug and Alcohol Center, Lincoln County Ambulance, the local funeral home and the local auto body shop to put on a mock crash and funeral for high school victims and staff. They reached approximately 200 people with their important message.

post_text:
Amazing Day for the Music Program!!!
David Larsen is the current concert and jazz band director at Spokane Falls Community College. Mr. Larsen directed the High School Honor Band at Bi-County Music Festival in March. Both junior high and high school bands had the opportunity to work with him this past spring at Large Group Festival in Spokane. Not only was he one of our adjudicators at the festival but he was the director that worked with us for a few minutes after our performance. He was gracious enough to come work with us today for a longer period of time. He taught us many new things that we hope to take with us next fall. However the most important thing he taught us was the importance of playing in a band until we're old. Music helps us in so many areas of our lives, the most important being that it makes it better. Thank you Mr. Larsen for the wealth of knowledge that you shared with us.
text:
Amazing Day for the Music Program!!!
David Larsen is the current concert and jazz band director at Spokane Falls Community College. Mr. Larsen directed the High School Honor Band at Bi-County Music Festival in March. Both junior high and high school bands had the opportunity to work with him this past spring at Large Group Festival in Spokane. Not only was he one of our adjudicators at the festival but he was the director that worked with us for a few minutes after our performance. He was gracious enough to come work with us today for a longer period of time. He taught us many new things that we hope to take with us next fall. However the most important thing he taught us was the importance of playing in a band until we're old. Music helps us in so many areas of our lives, the most important being that it makes it better. Thank you Mr. Larsen for the wealth of knowledge that you shared with us.

post_text:
Last night, the House and Senate reached a compromise on the "Hirst" water rights issue and moved forward to pass a Capital Budget for 2017. In addition, they also passed a bill to sell 4 billion in bonds to fund the state portion of construction projects.

The bills will be signed by the Governor and the Office of Financial Management (OFM) will proceed with a bond sale. They will notify OSPI when the funds are available and we will then receive a notice to proceed. This process will take 4-6 weeks before we can resume our bond project but we finally are back on track!

We will be preparing a new schedule in the next few weeks but should be able to see construction begin this spring!
text:
Last night, the House and Senate reached a compromise on the "Hirst" water rights issue and moved forward to pass a Capital Budget for 2017. In addition, they also passed a bill to sell 4 billion in bonds to fund the state portion of construction projects.

The bills will be signed by the Governor and the Office of Financial Management (OFM) will proceed with a bond sale. They will notify OSPI when the funds are available and we will then receive a notice to proceed. This process will take 4-6 weeks before we can resume our bond project but we finally are back on track!

We will be preparing a new schedule in the next few weeks but should be able to see construction begin this spring!

Reardan schools were in a modified lockdown today (students were not allowed to leave their building) while campus was searched. A young student reported seeing someone with a gun near the cars. Campus was searched and no evidence of a weapon was found. Students were dismissed at the regular time.
We will always take precautions to keep everyone safe! Thank you for your understanding.
